# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arm-trustzone
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Due to their low costs, low power consumption, and low heat generation, ARM processors are useful for light, portable, battery-powered devices, including smartphones, laptops, and tablet computers, as well as embedded systems.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] However, ARM processors are also used for desktops and servers, including Fugaku, the world's fastest supercomputer from 2020 to 2022.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] With over 230 billion ARM chips produced, since at least 2003, and with its dominance increasing every year, ARM is the most widely used family of instruction set architectures.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] There have been several generations of the ARM design.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The original ARM1 used a 32-bit internal structure but had a 26-bit address space that limited it to 64 MB of main memory.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] This limitation was removed in the ARMv3 series, which has a 32-bit address space, and several additional generations up to ARMv7 remained 32-bit.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Released in 2011, the ARMv8-A architecture added support for a 64-bit address space and 64-bit arithmetic with its new 32-bit fixed-length instruction set.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings has also released a series of additional instruction sets for different roles: the "Thumb" extensions add both 32- and 16-bit instructions for improved code density, while Jazelle added instructions for directly handling Java bytecode.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] More recent changes include the addition of simultaneous multithreading (SMT) for improved performance or fault tolerance.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn Computers' first widely successful design was the BBC Micro, introduced in December 1981.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] This was a relatively conventional machine based on the MOS Technology 6502 CPU but ran at roughly double the performance of competing designs like the Apple II due to its use of faster dynamic random-access memory (DRAM).
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Typical DRAM of the era ran at about 2 MHz; Acorn arranged a deal with Hitachi for a supply of faster 4 MHz parts.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Machines of the era generally shared memory between the processor and the framebuffer, which allowed the processor to quickly update the contents of the screen without having to perform separate input/output (I/O).
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] As the timing of the video display is exacting, the video hardware had to have priority access to that memory.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Due to a quirk of the 6502's design, the CPU left the memory untouched for half of the time.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Thus by running the CPU at 1 MHz, the video system could read data during those down times, taking up the total 2 MHz bandwidth of the RAM.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] In the BBC Micro, the use of 4 MHz RAM allowed the same technique to be used, but running at twice the speed.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] This allowed it to outperform any similar machine on the market.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] 1981 was also the year that the IBM Personal Computer was introduced.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Using the recently introduced Intel 8088, a 16-bit CPU compared to the 6502's 8-bit design, it offered higher overall performance.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Its introduction changed the desktop computer market radically: what had been largely a hobby and gaming market emerging over the prior five years began to change to a must-have business tool where the earlier 8-bit designs simply could not compete.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Even newer 32-bit designs were also coming to market, such as the Motorola 68000 and National Semiconductor NS32016.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn began considering how to compete in this market and produced a new paper design named the Acorn Business Computer.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] They set themselves the goal of producing a machine with ten times the performance of the BBC Micro, but at the same price.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] This would outperform and underprice the PC.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] At the same time, the recent introduction of the Apple Lisa brought the graphical user interface (GUI) concept to a wider audience and suggested the future belonged to machines with a GUI.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The Lisa, however, cost $9,995, as it was packed with support chips, large amounts of memory, and a hard disk drive, all very expensive then.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The engineers then began studying all of the CPU designs available.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Their conclusion about the existing 16-bit designs was that they were a lot more expensive and were still "a bit crap", offering only slightly higher performance than their BBC Micro design.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] They also almost always demanded a large number of support chips to operate even at that level, which drove up the cost of the computer as a whole.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] These systems would simply not hit the design goal.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] They also considered the new 32-bit designs, but these cost even more and had the same issues with support chips.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] According to Sophie Wilson, all the processors tested at that time performed about the same, with about a 4 Mbit/s bandwidth.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Two key events led Acorn down the path to ARM.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] One was the publication of a series of reports from the University of California, Berkeley, which suggested that a simple chip design could nevertheless have extremely high performance, much higher than the latest 32-bit designs on the market.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The second was a visit by Steve Furber and Sophie Wilson to the Western Design Center, a company run by Bill Mensch and his sister Kathryn, which had become the logical successor to the MOS team and was offering new versions like the WDC 65C02.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The Acorn team saw high school students producing chip layouts on Apple II machines, which suggested that anyone could do it.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] In contrast, a visit to another design firm working on modern 32-bit CPU revealed a team with over a dozen members who were already on revision H of their design and yet it still contained bugs.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] This cemented their late 1983 decision to begin their own CPU design, the Acorn RISC Machine.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The original Berkeley RISC designs were in some sense teaching systems, not designed specifically for outright performance.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] To the RISC's basic register-heavy and load/store concepts, ARM added a number of the well-received design notes of the 6502.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Primary among them was the ability to quickly service interrupts, which allowed the machines to offer reasonable input/output performance with no added external hardware.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] To offer interrupts with similar performance as the 6502, the ARM design limited its physical address space to 64 MB of total addressable space, requiring 26 bits of address.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] As instructions were 4 bytes (32 bits) long, and required to be aligned on 4-byte boundaries, the lower 2 bits of an instruction address were always zero.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] This meant the program counter (PC) only needed to be 24 bits, allowing it to be stored along with the eight bit processor flags in a single 32-bit register.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] That meant that upon receiving an interrupt, the entire machine state could be saved in a single operation, whereas had the PC been a full 32-bit value, it would require separate operations to store the PC and the status flags.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] This decision halved the interrupt overhead.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Another change, and among the most important in terms of practical real-world performance, was the modification of the instruction set to take advantage of page mode DRAM.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Recently introduced, page mode allowed subsequent accesses of memory to run twice as fast if they were roughly in the same location, or "page", in the DRAM chip.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Berkeley's design did not consider page mode and treated all memory equally.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM design added special vector-like memory access instructions, the "S-cycles", that could be used to fill or save multiple registers in a single page using page mode.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] This doubled memory performance when they could be used, and was especially important for graphics performance.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The Berkeley RISC designs used register windows to reduce the number of register saves and restores performed in procedure calls; the ARM design did not adopt this.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Wilson developed the instruction set, writing a simulation of the processor in BBC BASIC that ran on a BBC Micro with a second 6502 processor.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] This convinced Acorn engineers they were on the right track.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Wilson approached Acorn's CEO, Hermann Hauser, and requested more resources.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Hauser gave his approval and assembled a small team to design the actual processor based on Wilson's instruction set architecture.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The official Acorn RISC Machine project started in October 1983.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn chose VLSI Technology as the "silicon partner", as they were a source of ROMs and custom chips for Acorn.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn provided the design and VLSI provided the layout and production.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The first samples of ARM silicon worked properly when first received and tested on 26 April 1985.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Known as ARM1, these versions ran at 6 MHz.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The first ARM application was as a second processor for the BBC Micro, where it helped in developing simulation software to finish development of the support chips (VIDC, IOC, MEMC), and sped up the CAD software used in ARM2 development.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Wilson subsequently rewrote BBC BASIC in ARM assembly language.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The in-depth knowledge gained from designing the instruction set enabled the code to be very dense, making ARM BBC BASIC an extremely good test for any ARM emulator.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM Evaluations Systems featuring ARM1 CPUs and supplied as second processors for BBC Micro and Master machines, were made available from July 1986 under the Acorn OEM Products brand to developers and researchers.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The A500 Second Processor, an additional ARM1 based BBC Micro and Master second processor, featured the ARM support chipset (VIDC, IOC, MEMC), was capable of producing video output and operating near independently of the host BBC Micro.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The result of the simulations on the ARM1 boards led to the late 1986 introduction of the ARM2 design running at 8 MHz, and the early 1987 speed-bumped version at 10 to 12 MHz.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] A significant change in the underlying architecture was the addition of a Booth multiplier, whereas formerly multiplication had to be carried out in software.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Further, a new Fast Interrupt reQuest mode, FIQ for short, allowed registers 8 to 14 to be replaced as part of the interrupt itself.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] This meant FIQ requests did not have to save out their registers, further speeding interrupts.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The first use of the ARM2 was in internal Acorn A500 development machines, and the Acorn Archimedes personal computer models A305, A310, and A440, launched on the 6th June 1987.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] According to the Dhrystone benchmark, the ARM2 was roughly seven times the performance of a typical 7 MHz 68000-based system like the Amiga or Macintosh SE.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] It was twice as fast as an Intel 80386 running at 16 MHz, and about the same speed as a multi-processor VAX-11/784 superminicomputer.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The only systems that beat it were the Sun SPARC and MIPS R2000 RISC-based workstations.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Further, as the CPU was designed for high-speed I/O, it dispensed with many of the support chips seen in these machines; notably, it lacked any dedicated direct memory access (DMA) controller which was often found on workstations.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The graphics system was also simplified based on the same set of underlying assumptions about memory and timing.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The result was a dramatically simplified design, offering performance on par with expensive workstations but at a price point similar to contemporary desktops.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM2 featured a 32-bit data bus, 26-bit address space and 27 32-bit registers, of which 16 are accessible at any one time (including the PC).
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM2 had a transistor count of just 30,000, compared to Motorola's six-year-older 68000 model with around 68,000.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Much of this simplicity came from the lack of microcode, which represents about one-quarter to one-third of the 68000's transistors, and the lack of (like most CPUs of the day) a cache.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] This simplicity enabled the ARM2 to have a low power consumption and simpler thermal packaging by having fewer powered transistors.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Nevertheless, ARM2 offered better performance than the contemporary 1987 IBM PS/2 Model 50, which initially utilised an Intel 80286, offering 1.8 MIPS @ 10 MHz, and later in 1987, the 2 MIPS of the PS/2 70, with its Intel 386 DX @ 16 MHz.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] A successor, ARM3, was produced with a 4 KB cache, which further improved performance.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The address bus was extended to 32 bits in the ARM6, but program code still had to lie within the first 64 MB of memory in 26-bit compatibility mode, due to the reserved bits for the status flags.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 1988, Sanyo became a worldwide second source for the ARM2 and associated chipset under an agreement with VLSI Technology.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] In the late 1980s, Apple Computer and VLSI Technology started working with Acorn on newer versions of the ARM core.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 1990, Acorn spun off the design team into a new company named Advanced RISC Machines Ltd., which became ARM Ltd. when its parent company, Arm Holdings plc, floated on the London Stock Exchange and Nasdaq in 1998.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The new Apple–ARM work would eventually evolve into the ARM6, first released in early 1992.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Apple used the ARM6-based ARM610 as the basis for their Apple Newton PDA.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 1994, Acorn used the ARM610 as the main central processing unit (CPU) in their RiscPC computers.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] DEC licensed the ARMv4 architecture and produced the StrongARM.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] At 233 MHz, this CPU drew only one watt (newer versions draw far less).
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] This work was later passed to Intel as part of a lawsuit settlement, and Intel took the opportunity to supplement their i960 line with the StrongARM.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Intel later developed its own high performance implementation named XScale, which it has since sold to Marvell.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Transistor count of the ARM core remained essentially the same throughout these changes; ARM2 had 30,000 transistors, while ARM6 grew only to 35,000.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2005, about 98% of all mobile phones sold used at least one ARM processor.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2010, producers of chips based on ARM architectures reported shipments of 6.1 billion ARM-based processors, representing 95% of smartphones, 35% of digital televisions and set-top boxes, and 10% of mobile computers.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2011, the 32-bit ARM architecture was the most widely used architecture in mobile devices and the most popular 32-bit one in embedded systems.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2013, 10 billion were produced and "ARM-based chips are found in nearly 60 percent of the world's mobile devices".
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings's primary business is selling IP cores, which licensees use to create microcontrollers (MCUs), CPUs, and systems-on-chips based on those cores.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The original design manufacturer combines the ARM core with other parts to produce a complete device, typically one that can be built in existing semiconductor fabrication plants (fabs) at low cost and still deliver substantial performance.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The most successful implementation has been the ARM7TDMI with hundreds of millions sold.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Atmel has been a precursor design center in the ARM7TDMI-based embedded system.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM architectures used in smartphones, PDAs and other mobile devices range from ARMv5 to ARMv8-A.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2009, some manufacturers introduced netbooks based on ARM architecture CPUs, in direct competition with netbooks based on Intel Atom.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings offers a variety of licensing terms, varying in cost and deliverables.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings provides to all licensees an integratable hardware description of the ARM core as well as complete software development toolset (compiler, debugger, software development kit), and the right to sell manufactured silicon containing the ARM CPU.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] SoC packages integrating ARM's core designs include Nvidia Tegra's first three generations, CSR plc's Quatro family, ST-Ericsson's Nova and NovaThor, Silicon Labs's Precision32 MCU, Texas Instruments's OMAP products, Samsung's Hummingbird and Exynos products, Apple's A4, A5, and A5X, and NXP's i.MX.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Fabless licensees, who wish to integrate an ARM core into their own chip design, are usually only interested in acquiring a ready-to-manufacture verified semiconductor intellectual property core.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] For these customers, Arm Holdings delivers a gate netlist description of the chosen ARM core, along with an abstracted simulation model and test programs to aid design integration and verification.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] More ambitious customers, including integrated device manufacturers (IDM) and foundry operators, choose to acquire the processor IP in synthesizable RTL (Verilog) form.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] With the synthesizable RTL, the customer has the ability to perform architectural level optimisations and extensions.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] This allows the designer to achieve exotic design goals not otherwise possible with an unmodified netlist (high clock speed, very low power consumption, instruction set extensions, etc.).
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] While Arm Holdings does not grant the licensee the right to resell the ARM architecture itself, licensees may freely sell manufactured products such as chip devices, evaluation boards and complete systems.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Merchant foundries can be a special case; not only are they allowed to sell finished silicon containing ARM cores, they generally hold the right to re-manufacture ARM cores for other customers.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings prices its IP based on perceived value.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Lower performing ARM cores typically have lower licence costs than higher performing cores.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] In implementation terms, a synthesisable core costs more than a hard macro (blackbox) core.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Complicating price matters, a merchant foundry that holds an ARM licence, such as Samsung or Fujitsu, can offer fab customers reduced licensing costs.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] In exchange for acquiring the ARM core through the foundry's in-house design services, the customer can reduce or eliminate payment of ARM's upfront licence fee.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Compared to dedicated semiconductor foundries (such as TSMC and UMC) without in-house design services, Fujitsu/Samsung charge two- to three-times more per manufactured wafer.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] For low to mid volume applications, a design service foundry offers lower overall pricing (through subsidisation of the licence fee).
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] For high volume mass-produced parts, the long term cost reduction achievable through lower wafer pricing reduces the impact of ARM's NRE (non-recurring engineering) costs, making the dedicated foundry a better choice.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] In February 2016, ARM announced the Built on ARM Cortex Technology licence, often shortened to Built on Cortex (BoC) licence.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] This licence allows companies to partner with ARM and make modifications to ARM Cortex designs.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] These design modifications will not be shared with other companies.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] These semi-custom core designs also have brand freedom, for example Kryo 280.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Companies that are current licensees of Built on ARM Cortex Technology include Qualcomm.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Companies can also obtain an ARM *architectural licence* for designing their own CPU cores using the ARM instruction sets.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] These cores must comply fully with the ARM architecture.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Companies that have designed cores that implement an ARM architecture include Apple, AppliedMicro (now: Ampere Computing), Broadcom, Cavium (now: Marvell), Digital Equipment Corporation, Intel, Nvidia, Qualcomm, Samsung Electronics, Fujitsu, and NUVIA Inc.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] On 16 July 2019, ARM announced ARM Flexible Access.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM Flexible Access provides unlimited access to included ARM intellectual property (IP) for development.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Per product licence fees are required once a customer reaches foundry tapeout or prototyping.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] 75% of ARM's most recent IP over the last two years are included in ARM Flexible Access.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARMv3 included a compatibility mode to support the 26-bit addresses of earlier versions of the architecture.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] This compatibility mode is *optional* in ARMv4, and removed entirely in ARMv5.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm provides a list of vendors who implement ARM cores in their design (application specific standard products (ASSP), microprocessor and microcontrollers).
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM cores are used in a number of products, particularly PDAs and smartphones.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Some computing examples are Microsoft's first generation Surface, Surface 2 and Pocket PC devices (following 2002), Apple's iPads, and Asus's Eee Pad Transformer tablet computers, and several Chromebook laptops.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] Others include Apple's iPhone smartphones and iPod portable media players, Canon PowerShot digital cameras, Nintendo Switch hybrid, the Wii security processor and 3DS handheld game consoles, and TomTom turn-by-turn navigation systems.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2005, Arm took part in the development of Manchester University's computer SpiNNaker, which used ARM cores to simulate the human brain.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM chips are also used in Raspberry Pi, BeagleBoard, BeagleBone, PandaBoard, and other single-board computers, because they are very small, inexpensive, and consume very little power.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The 32-bit ARM architecture (**ARM32**), such as **ARMv7-A** (implementing AArch32; see section on Armv8-A for more on it), was the most widely used architecture in mobile devices as of 2011.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Although the architecture profiles were first defined for ARMv7, ARM subsequently defined the ARMv6-M architecture (used by the Cortex M0/M0+/M1) as a subset of the ARMv7-M profile with fewer instructions.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] 26-bit addressing - obsolete as of June 2000.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Multiply and multiply-accumulate instructions; coprocessor support - all variants obsolete as of June 2000.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] 32-bit addressing - all variants obsolete as of July 2005.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] , the former of which supports the 32-bit ARM instruction set, called A32, and the Thumb-2 instruction set, called T32, and the latter of which supports a new instruction set with 32 64-bit registers, called A64.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Except in the M-profile, the 32-bit ARM architecture specifies several CPU modes, depending on the implemented architecture features.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] At any moment in time, the CPU can be in only one mode, but it can switch modes due to external events (interrupts) or programmatically.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The original ARM implementation was hardwired without microcode, like the much simpler 8-bit 6502 processor used in prior Acorn microcomputers.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM includes integer arithmetic operations for add, subtract, and multiply; some versions of the architecture also support divide operations.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM supports 32-bit × 32-bit multiplies with either a 32-bit result or 64-bit result, though Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 cores do not support 64-bit results.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some ARM cores also support 16-bit × 16-bit and 32-bit × 16-bit multiplies.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Registers R0 through R7 are the same across all CPU modes; they are never banked.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Registers R8 through R12 are the same across all CPU modes except FIQ mode.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] FIQ mode has its own distinct R8 through R12 registers.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] R13 and R14 are banked across all privileged CPU modes except system mode.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] That is, each mode that can be entered because of an exception has its own R13 and R14.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] These registers generally contain the stack pointer and the return address from function calls, respectively.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Current Program Status Register (CPSR) has the following 32 bits.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Almost every ARM instruction has a conditional execution feature called predication, which is implemented with a 4-bit condition code selector (the predicate).
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] To allow for unconditional execution, one of the four-bit codes causes the instruction to be always executed.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Most other CPU architectures only have condition codes on branch instructions.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Though the predicate takes up four of the 32 bits in an instruction code, and thus cuts down significantly on the encoding bits available for displacements in memory access instructions, it avoids branch instructions when generating code for small `if` statements.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Apart from eliminating the branch instructions themselves, this preserves the fetch/decode/execute pipeline at the cost of only one cycle per skipped instruction.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] An algorithm that provides a good example of conditional execution is the subtraction-based Euclidean algorithm for computing the greatest common divisor.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] which avoids the branches around the `then` and `else` clauses.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] If `r0` and `r1` are equal then neither of the `SUB` instructions will be executed, eliminating the need for a conditional branch to implement the `while` check at the top of the loop, for example had `SUBLE` (less than or equal) been used.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] One of the ways that Thumb code provides a more dense encoding is to remove the four-bit selector from non-branch instructions.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] This results in the typical ARM program being denser than expected with fewer memory accesses; thus the pipeline is used more efficiently.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM processor also has features rarely seen in other RISC architectures, such as PC-relative addressing (indeed, on the 32-bit ARM the PC is one of its 16 registers) and pre- and post-increment addressing modes.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM instruction set has increased over time.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some early ARM processors (before ARM7TDMI), for example, have no instruction to store a two-byte quantity.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM7 and earlier implementations have a three-stage pipeline; the stages being fetch, decode, and execute.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Higher-performance designs, such as the ARM9, have deeper pipelines: Cortex-A8 has thirteen stages.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Additional implementation changes for higher performance include a faster adder and more extensive branch prediction logic.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The difference between the ARM7DI and ARM7DMI cores, for example, was an improved multiplier; hence the added "M".
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM architecture (pre-Armv8) provides a non-intrusive way of extending the instruction set using "coprocessors" that can be addressed using MCR, MRC, MRRC, MCRR, and similar instructions.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The coprocessor space is divided logically into 16 coprocessors with numbers from 0 to 15, coprocessor 15 (cp15) being reserved for some typical control functions like managing the caches and MMU operation on processors that have one.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] In ARM-based machines, peripheral devices are usually attached to the processor by mapping their physical registers into ARM memory space, into the coprocessor space, or by connecting to another device (a bus) that in turn attaches to the processor.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Coprocessor accesses have lower latency, so some peripherals—for example, an XScale interrupt controller—are accessible in both ways: through memory and through coprocessors.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] In other cases, chip designers only integrate hardware using the coprocessor mechanism.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, an image processing engine might be a small ARM7TDMI core combined with a coprocessor that has specialised operations to support a specific set of HDTV transcoding primitives.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] All modern ARM processors include hardware debugging facilities, allowing software debuggers to perform operations such as halting, stepping, and breakpointing of code starting from reset.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] These facilities are built using JTAG support, though some newer cores optionally support ARM's own two-wire "SWD" protocol.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] In ARM7TDMI cores, the "D" represented JTAG debug support, and the "I" represented presence of an "EmbeddedICE" debug module.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] For ARM7 and ARM9 core generations, EmbeddedICE over JTAG was a de facto debug standard, though not architecturally guaranteed.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARMv7 architecture defines basic debug facilities at an architectural level.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] These include breakpoints, watchpoints and instruction execution in a "Debug Mode"; similar facilities were also available with EmbeddedICE.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Both "halt mode" and "monitor" mode debugging are supported.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The actual transport mechanism used to access the debug facilities is not architecturally specified, but implementations generally include JTAG support.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] There is a separate ARM "CoreSight" debug architecture, which is not architecturally required by ARMv7 processors.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Debug Access Port (DAP) is an implementation of an ARM Debug Interface.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] There are two different supported implementations, the Serial Wire JTAG Debug Port (SWJ-DP) and the Serial Wire Debug Port (SW-DP).
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] CMSIS-DAP is a standard interface that describes how various debugging software on a host PC can communicate over USB to firmware running on a hardware debugger, which in turn talks over SWD or JTAG to a CoreSight-enabled ARM Cortex CPU.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] To improve the ARM architecture for digital signal processing and multimedia applications, DSP instructions were added to the instruction set.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] These are signified by an "E" in the name of the ARMv5TE and ARMv5TEJ architectures.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The new instructions are common in digital signal processor (DSP) architectures.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] They include variations on signed multiply–accumulate, saturated add and subtract, and count leading zeros.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] First introduced in 1999, this extension of the core instruction set contrasted with ARM's earlier DSP coprocessor known as Piccolo, which employed a distinct, incompatible instruction set whose execution involved a separate program counter.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Piccolo instructions employed a distinct register file of sixteen 32-bit registers, with some instructions combining registers for use as 48-bit accumulators and other instructions addressing 16-bit half-registers.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some instructions were able to operate on two such 16-bit values in parallel.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Communication with the Piccolo register file involved *load to Piccolo* and *store from Piccolo* coprocessor instructions via two buffers of eight 32-bit entries.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Described as reminiscent of other approaches, notably Hitachi's SH-DSP and Motorola's 68356, Piccolo did not employ dedicated local memory and relied on the bandwidth of the ARM core for DSP operand retrieval, impacting concurrent performance.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Piccolo's distinct instruction set also proved not to be a "good compiler target".
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Introduced in the ARMv6 architecture, this was a precursor to Advanced SIMD, also named Neon.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Jazelle DBX (Direct Bytecode eXecution) is a technique that allows Java bytecode to be executed directly in the ARM architecture as a third execution state (and instruction set) alongside the existing ARM and Thumb-mode.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Support for this state is signified by the "J" in the ARMv5TEJ architecture, and in ARM9EJ-S and ARM7EJ-S core names.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Support for this state is required starting in ARMv6 (except for the ARMv7-M profile), though newer cores only include a trivial implementation that provides no hardware acceleration.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] To improve compiled code density, processors since the ARM7TDMI (released in 1994) have featured the *Thumb* compressed instruction set, which have their own state.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] (The "T" in "TDMI" indicates the Thumb feature.) When in this state, the processor executes the Thumb instruction set, a compact 16-bit encoding for a subset of the ARM instruction set.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Most of the Thumb instructions are directly mapped to normal ARM instructions.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The space saving comes from making some of the instruction operands implicit and limiting the number of possibilities compared to the ARM instructions executed in the ARM instruction set state.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] In Thumb, the 16-bit opcodes have less functionality.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, only branches can be conditional, and many opcodes are restricted to accessing only half of all of the CPU's general-purpose registers.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The shorter opcodes give improved code density overall, even though some operations require extra instructions.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] In situations where the memory port or bus width is constrained to less than 32 bits, the shorter Thumb opcodes allow increased performance compared with 32-bit ARM code, as less program code may need to be loaded into the processor over the constrained memory bandwidth.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Unlike processor architectures with variable length (16- or 32-bit) instructions, such as the Cray-1 and Hitachi SuperH, the ARM and Thumb instruction sets exist independently of each other.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Embedded hardware, such as the Game Boy Advance, typically have a small amount of RAM accessible with a full 32-bit datapath; the majority is accessed via a 16-bit or narrower secondary datapath.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] In this situation, it usually makes sense to compile Thumb code and hand-optimise a few of the most CPU-intensive sections using full 32-bit ARM instructions, placing these wider instructions into the 32-bit bus accessible memory.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first processor with a Thumb instruction decoder was the ARM7TDMI.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] All processors supporting 32-bit instruction sets, starting with ARM9, and including XScale, have included a Thumb instruction decoder.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] It includes instructions adopted from the Hitachi SuperH (1992), which was licensed by ARM.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM's smallest processor families (Cortex M0 and M1) implement only the 16-bit Thumb instruction set for maximum performance in lowest cost applications.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM processors that don't support 32-bit addressing also omit Thumb.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Thumb-2 extends the Thumb instruction set with bit-field manipulation, table branches and conditional execution.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] At the same time, the ARM instruction set was extended to maintain equivalent functionality in both instruction sets.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] A new "Unified Assembly Language" (UAL) supports generation of either Thumb or ARM instructions from the same source code; versions of Thumb seen on ARMv7 processors are essentially as capable as ARM code (including the ability to write interrupt handlers).
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] This requires a bit of care, and use of a new "IT" (if-then) instruction, which permits up to four successive instructions to execute based on a tested condition, or on its inverse.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] When compiling into ARM code, this is ignored, but when compiling into Thumb it generates an actual instruction.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] All ARMv7 chips support the Thumb instruction set.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] All chips in the Cortex-A series that support ARMv7, all Cortex-R series, and all ARM11 series support both "ARM instruction set state" and "Thumb instruction set state", while chips in the Cortex-M series support only the Thumb instruction set.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] New features provided by ThumbEE include automatic null pointer checks on every load and store instruction, an instruction to perform an array bounds check, and special instructions that call a handler.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] In addition, because it utilises Thumb-2 technology, ThumbEE provides access to registers r8–r15 (where the Jazelle/DBX Java VM state is held).
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Handlers are small sections of frequently called code, commonly used to implement high level languages, such as allocating memory for a new object.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] These changes come from repurposing a handful of opcodes, and knowing the core is in the new ThumbEE state.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] On 23 November 2011, Arm deprecated any use of the ThumbEE instruction set, and Armv8 removes support for ThumbEE.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some devices such as the ARM Cortex-A8 have a cut-down *VFPLite* module instead of a full VFP module, and require roughly ten times more clock cycles per float operation.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Pre-Armv8 architecture implemented floating-point/SIMD with the coprocessor interface.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Other floating-point and/or SIMD units found in ARM-based processors using the coprocessor interface include FPA, FPE, iwMMXt, some of which were implemented in software by trapping but could have been implemented in hardware.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] They provide some of the same functionality as VFP but are not opcode-compatible with it.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] FPA10 also provides extended precision, but implements correct rounding (required by IEEE 754) only in single precision.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] An optional extension to the ARM instruction set in the ARMv5TE, ARMv5TEJ and ARMv6 architectures.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on most Cortex-A8 and A9 ARMv7 processors.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] It is backward-compatible with VFPv2, except that it cannot trap floating-point exceptions.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] VFPv3 has 32 64-bit FPU registers as standard, adds VCVT instructions to convert between scalar, float and double, adds immediate mode to VMOV such that constants can be loaded into FPU registers.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] As above, but with only 16 64-bit FPU registers.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on Cortex-A12 and A15 ARMv7 processors, Cortex-A7 optionally has VFPv4-D32 in the case of an FPU with Neon.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] As above, but it has only 16 64-bit FPU registers.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on Cortex-A5 and A7 processors in the case of an FPU without Neon.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on Cortex-M7 when single and double-precision floating-point core option exists.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] In Debian Linux and derivatives such as Ubuntu and Linux Mint, **armhf** (**ARM hard float**) refers to the ARMv7 architecture including the additional VFP3-D16 floating-point hardware extension (and Thumb-2) above.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Software packages and cross-compiler tools use the armhf vs. arm/armel suffixes to differentiate.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The *Advanced SIMD* extension (also known as *Neon* or "MPE" Media Processing Engine) is a combined 64- and 128-bit SIMD instruction set that provides standardised acceleration for media and signal processing applications.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Neon is included in all Cortex-A8 devices, but is optional in Cortex-A9 devices.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Neon can execute MP3 audio decoding on CPUs running at 10 MHz, and can run the GSM adaptive multi-rate (AMR) speech codec at 13 MHz.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] It features a comprehensive instruction set, separate register files, and independent execution hardware.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Neon supports 8-, 16-, 32-, and 64-bit integer and single-precision (32-bit) floating-point data and SIMD operations for handling audio and video processing as well as graphics and gaming processing.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] In Neon, the SIMD supports up to 16 operations at the same time.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Neon hardware shares the same floating-point registers as used in VFP.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Devices such as the ARM Cortex-A8 and Cortex-A9 support 128-bit vectors, but will execute with 64 bits at a time, whereas some more powerful CPUs such as Cortex-A15 can execute 128 bits at a time.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] A quirk of Neon in Armv7 devices is that it flushes all subnormal numbers to zero, and as a result the GCC compiler will not use it unless `-funsafe-math-optimizations`, which allows losing denormals, is turned on.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] "Enhanced" Neon defined since Armv8 does not have this quirk, but as of GCC 8.2 the same flag is still required to enable Neon instructions.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] On the other hand, GCC does consider Neon safe on AArch64 for Armv8.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] ProjectNe10 is ARM's first open-source project (from its inception; while they acquired an older project, now named Mbed TLS).
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Ne10 library is a set of common, useful functions written in both Neon and C (for compatibility).
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The library was created to allow developers to use Neon optimisations without learning Neon, but it also serves as a set of highly optimised Neon intrinsic and assembly code examples for common DSP, arithmetic, and image processing routines.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Helium is the M-Profile Vector Extension (MVE).
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] It adds more than 150 scalar and vector instructions.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Security Extensions, marketed as TrustZone Technology, is in ARMv6KZ and later application profile architectures.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] It provides a low-cost alternative to adding another dedicated security core to an SoC, by providing two virtual processors backed by hardware based access control.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] This lets the application core switch between two states, referred to as *worlds* (to reduce confusion with other names for capability domains), to prevent information leaking from the more trusted world (the *Secure world*) to the less trusted world (the *Normal world*).
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] This world switch is generally orthogonal to all other capabilities of the processor, thus each world can operate independently of the other while using the same core.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Memory and peripherals are then made aware of the operating world of the core and may use this to provide access control to secrets and code on the device.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Typically, a rich operating system is run in the less trusted world, with smaller security-specialised code in the more trusted world, aiming to reduce the attack surface.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Typical applications include DRM functionality for controlling the use of media on ARM-based devices, and preventing any unapproved use of the device.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] In practice, since the specific implementation details of proprietary TrustZone implementations have not been publicly disclosed for review, it is unclear what level of assurance is provided for a given threat model, but they are not immune from attack.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Open Virtualization is an open source implementation of the trusted world architecture for TrustZone.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] AMD has licensed and incorporated TrustZone technology into its Secure Processor Technology.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] AMD's APUs include a Cortex-A5 processor for handling secure processing, which is enabled in some, but not all products.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] In fact, the Cortex-A5 TrustZone core had been included in earlier AMD products, but was not enabled due to time constraints.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Samsung Knox uses TrustZone for purposes such as detecting modifications to the kernel, storing certificates and attestating keys.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Security Extension, marketed as TrustZone for Armv8-M Technology, was introduced in the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] While containing similar concepts to TrustZone for Armv8-A, it has a different architectural design, as world switching is performed using branch instructions instead of using exceptions.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] It also supports safe interleaved interrupt handling from either world regardless of the current security state.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Together these features provide low latency calls to the secure world and responsive interrupt handling.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM provides a reference stack of secure world code in the form of Trusted Firmware for M and PSA Certified.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] As of ARMv6, the ARM architecture supports no-execute page protection, which is referred to as *XN*, for *eXecute Never*.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Large Physical Address Extension (LPAE), which extends the physical address size from 32 bits to 40 bits, was added to the Armv7-A architecture in 2011.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The physical address size may be even larger in processors based on the 64-bit (Armv8-A) architecture.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, it is 44 bits in Cortex-A75 and Cortex-A65AE.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The **Armv8-R** and **Armv8-M** architectures, announced after the Armv8-A architecture, share some features with Armv8-A.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] However, Armv8-M does not include any 64-bit AArch64 instructions, and Armv8-R originally did not include any AArch64 instructions; those instructions were added to Armv8-R later.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Armv8.1-M architecture, announced in February 2019, is an enhancement of the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Announced in October 2011, **Armv8-A** (often called ARMv8 while the Armv8-R is also available) represents a fundamental change to the ARM architecture.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] It supports two *Execution states*: a 64-bit state named *AArch64* and a 32-bit state named *AArch32*.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] In the AArch64 state, a new 64-bit *A64* instruction set is supported; in the AArch32 state, two instruction sets are supported: the original 32-bit instruction set, named *A32*, and the 32-bit Thumb-2 instruction set, named *T32*.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] AArch32 provides user-space compatibility with Armv7-A.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The processor state can change on an Exception level change; this allows 32-bit applications to be executed in AArch32 state under a 64-bit OS whose kernel executes in AArch64 state, and allows a 32-bit OS to run in AArch32 state under the control of a 64-bit hypervisor running in AArch64 state.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM announced their Cortex-A53 and Cortex-A57 cores on 30 October 2012.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Apple was the first to release an Armv8-A compatible core in a consumer product (Apple A7 in iPhone 5S).
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] AppliedMicro, using an FPGA, was the first to demo Armv8-A.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first Armv8-A SoC from Samsung is the Exynos 5433 used in the Galaxy Note 4, which features two clusters of four Cortex-A57 and Cortex-A53 cores in a big.LITTLE configuration; but it will run only in AArch32 mode.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] To both AArch32 and AArch64, Armv8-A makes VFPv3/v4 and advanced SIMD (Neon) standard.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] It also adds cryptography instructions supporting AES, SHA-1/SHA-256 and finite field arithmetic.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] AArch64 was introduced in Armv8-A and its subsequent revision.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] AArch64 is not included in the 32-bit Armv8-R and Armv8-M architectures.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] An ARMv8-A processor can support one or both of AArch32 and AArch64; it may support AArch32 and AArch64 at lower Exception levels and only AArch64 at higher Exception levels.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, the ARM Cortex-A32 supports only AArch32, the ARM Cortex-A34 supports only AArch64, and the ARM Cortex-A72 supports both AArch64 and AArch32.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] An ARMv9-A processor must support AArch64 at all Exception levels, and may support AArch32 at EL0.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Optional AArch64 support was added to the Armv8-R profile, with the first ARM core implementing it being the Cortex-R82.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Announced in March 2021, the updated architecture places a focus on secure execution and compartmentalisation.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first ARMv9-A processors were released later that year, including the Cortex-A510, Cortex-A710 and Cortex-X2.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Arm SystemReady is a compliance program that helps ensure the interoperability of an operating system on Arm-based hardware from datacenter servers to industrial edge and IoT devices.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The key building blocks of the program are the specifications for minimum hardware and firmware requirements that the operating systems and hypervisors can rely upon.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] These specifications are co-developed by Arm and its partners in the System Architecture Advisory Committee (SystemArchAC).
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Architecture Compliance Suite (ACS) is the test tools that help to check the compliance of these specifications.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Arm SystemReady Requirements Specification documents the requirements of the certifications.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] This program was introduced by Arm in 2020 at the first DevSummit event.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Its predecessor Arm ServerReady was introduced in 2018 at the Arm TechCon event.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified, formerly named Platform Security Architecture, is an architecture-agnostic security framework and evaluation scheme.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] It is intended to help secure Internet of things (IoT) devices built on system-on-a-chip (SoC) processors.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] It was introduced to increase security where a full trusted execution environment is too large or complex.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The architecture was introduced by Arm in 2017 at the annual TechCon event.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Although the scheme is architecture agnostic, it was first implemented on Arm Cortex-M processor cores intended for microcontroller use.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified includes freely available threat models and security analyses that demonstrate the process for deciding on security features in common IoT products.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] It also provides freely downloadable application programming interface (API) packages, architectural specifications, open-source firmware implementations, and related test suites.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Following the development of the architecture security framework in 2017, the PSA Certified assurance scheme launched two years later at Embedded World in 2019.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified offers a multi-level security evaluation scheme for chip vendors, OS providers and IoT device makers.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Embedded World presentation introduced chip vendors to Level 1 Certification.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] A draft of Level 2 protection was presented at the same time.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Level 2 certification became a usable standard in February 2020.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The certification was created by PSA Joint Stakeholders to enable a security-by-design approach for a diverse set of IoT products.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified specifications are implementation and architecture agnostic, as a result they can be applied to any chip, software or device.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The certification also removes industry fragmentation for IoT product manufacturers and developers.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first 32-bit ARM-based personal computer, the Acorn Archimedes, was originally intended to run an ambitious operating system called ARX.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] The machines shipped with RISC OS, which was also used on later ARM-based systems from Acorn and other vendors.
[src:arm-trustzone/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some early Acorn machines were also able to run a Unix port called RISC iX.
[src:arm-trustzone/hardware-security] A hardware security module (HSM) is a physical computing device that safeguards and manages digital keys for strong authentication and provides cryptoprocessing.
[src:arm-trustzone/hardware-security] These modules traditionally come in the form of a plug-in card or an external device that attaches directly to a computer or network server.
[src:arm-trustzone/hardware-security] Some providers in this discipline consider that the key difference between hardware security and software security is that hardware security is implemented using "non-Turing-machine" logic (raw combinatorial logic or simple state machines).
[src:arm-trustzone/hardware-security] One approach, referred to as "hardsec", uses FPGAs to implement non-Turing-machine security controls as a way of combining the security of hardware with the flexibility of software.
[src:arm-trustzone/hardware-security] Hardware backdoors are backdoors in hardware.
[src:arm-trustzone/hardware-security] Conceptionally related, a hardware Trojan (HT) is a malicious modification of electronic system, particularly in the context of integrated circuit.
[src:arm-trustzone/hardware-security] A physical unclonable function (PUF) is a physical entity that is embodied in a physical structure and is easy to evaluate but hard to predict.
[src:arm-trustzone/hardware-security] Further, an individual PUF device must be easy to make but practically impossible to duplicate, even given the exact manufacturing process that produced it.
[src:arm-trustzone/hardware-security] In this respect it is the hardware analog of a one-way function.
[src:arm-trustzone/hardware-security] The name "physical unclonable function" might be a little misleading as some PUFs are clonable, and most PUFs are noisy and therefore do not achieve the requirements for a function.
[src:arm-trustzone/hardware-security] Today, PUFs are usually implemented in integrated circuits and are typically used in applications with high security requirements.
[src:arm-trustzone/hardware-security] Many attacks on sensitive data and resources reported by organizations occur from within the organization itself.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] In computer science, **hierarchical protection domains**, often called **protection rings**, are mechanisms to protect data and functionality from faults (by improving fault tolerance) and malicious behavior (by providing computer security).
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Computer operating systems provide different levels of access to resources.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] A protection ring is one of two or more hierarchical *levels* or *layers* of privilege within the architecture of a computer system.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] This is generally hardware-enforced by some CPU architectures that provide different CPU modes at the hardware or microcode level.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Rings are arranged in a hierarchy from most privileged (most trusted, usually numbered zero) to least privileged (least trusted, usually with the highest ring number).
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] On most operating systems, Ring 0 is the level with the most privileges and interacts most directly with the physical hardware such as certain CPU functionality (e.g. the control registers) and I/O controllers.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Special mechanisms are provided to allow an outer ring to access an inner ring's resources in a predefined manner, as opposed to allowing arbitrary usage.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Correctly gating access between rings can improve security by preventing programs from one ring or privilege level from misusing resources intended for programs in another.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] For example, spyware running as a user program in Ring 3 should be prevented from turning on a web camera without informing the user, since hardware access should be a Ring 1 function reserved for device drivers.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Programs such as web browsers running in higher numbered rings must request access to the network, a resource restricted to a lower numbered ring.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] X86S, a canceled Intel architecture published in 2024, has only ring 0 and ring 3.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Ring 1 and 2 were to be removed under X86S since modern operating systems never utilize them.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Multiple rings of protection were among the most revolutionary concepts introduced by the Multics operating system, a highly secure predecessor of today's Unix family of operating systems.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] However, most general-purpose systems use only two rings, even if the hardware they run on provides more CPU modes than that.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] For example, Windows 7 and Windows Server 2008 (and their predecessors) use only two rings, with ring 0 corresponding to kernel mode and ring 3 to user mode, because earlier versions of Windows NT ran on processors that supported only two protection levels.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Many modern CPU architectures (including the popular Intel x86 architecture) include some form of ring protection, although the Windows NT operating system, like Unix, does not fully utilize this feature.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] OS/2 does, to some extent, use three rings: ring 0 for kernel code and device drivers, ring 2 for privileged code (user programs with I/O access permissions), and ring 3 for unprivileged code (nearly all user programs).
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Under DOS, the kernel, drivers and applications typically run on ring 3 (however, this is exclusive to the case where protected-mode drivers or DOS extenders are used; as a real-mode OS, the system runs with effectively no protection), whereas 386 memory managers such as EMM386 run at ring 0.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] In addition to this, DR-DOS' EMM386 3.xx can optionally run some modules (such as DPMS) on ring 1 instead.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] OpenVMS uses four modes called (in order of decreasing privileges) Kernel, Executive, Supervisor and User.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] The original Multics system had eight rings, but many modern systems have fewer.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] The hardware remains aware of the current ring of the executing instruction thread at all times, with the help of a special machine register.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] In some systems, areas of virtual memory are instead assigned ring numbers in hardware.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] One example is the Data General Eclipse MV/8000, in which the top three bits of the program counter (PC) served as the ring register.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Thus code executing with the virtual PC set to 0xE200000, for example, would automatically be in ring 7, and calling a subroutine in a different section of memory would automatically cause a ring transfer.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] The hardware severely restricts the ways in which control can be passed from one ring to another, and also enforces restrictions on the types of memory access that can be performed across rings.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] The hardware restrictions are designed to limit opportunities for accidental or malicious breaches of security.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] In addition, the most privileged ring may be given special capabilities (such as real memory addressing that bypasses the virtual memory hardware).
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] ARM version 7 architecture implements three privilege levels: application (PL0), operating system (PL1), and hypervisor (PL2).
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Unusually, level 0 (PL0) is the least-privileged level, while level 2 is the most-privileged level.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] ARM version 8 implements four exception levels: application (EL0), operating system (EL1), hypervisor (EL2), and secure monitor / firmware (EL3), for AArch64 and AArch32.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Ring protection can be combined with processor modes (master/kernel/privileged/supervisor mode versus slave/unprivileged/user mode) in some systems.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Operating systems running on hardware supporting both may use both forms of protection or only one.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Effective use of ring architecture requires close cooperation between hardware and the operating system.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Operating systems designed to work on multiple hardware platforms may make only limited use of rings if they are not present on every supported platform.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Often the security model is simplified to "kernel" and "user" even if hardware provides finer granularity through rings.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] In computer terms, *supervisor mode* is a hardware-mediated flag that can be changed by code running in system-level software.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] System-level tasks or threads may have this flag set while they are running, whereas user-level applications will not.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] This flag determines whether it would be possible to execute machine code operations such as modifying registers for various descriptor tables, or performing operations such as disabling interrupts.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] The idea of having two different modes to operate in comes from "with more power comes more responsibility" – a program in supervisor mode is trusted never to fail, since a failure may cause the whole computer system to crash.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Supervisor mode is "an execution mode on some processors which enables execution of all instructions, including privileged instructions.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] It may also give access to a different address space, to memory management hardware and to other peripherals.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] In a monolithic kernel, the operating system runs in supervisor mode and the applications run in user mode.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Other types of operating systems, like those with an exokernel or microkernel, do not necessarily share this behavior.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Most processors have at least two different modes.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] The x86-processors have four different modes divided into four different rings.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Programs that run in Ring 0 can do *anything* with the system, and code that runs in Ring 3 should be able to fail at any time without impact to the rest of the computer system.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Ring 1 and Ring 2 are rarely used, but could be configured with different levels of access.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] In most existing systems, switching from user mode to kernel mode has an associated high cost in performance.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] It has been measured, on the basic request `getpid`, to cost 1000–1500 cycles on most machines.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Of these just around 100 are for the actual switch (70 from user to kernel space, and 40 back), the rest is "kernel overhead".
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] In the L3 microkernel, the minimization of this overhead reduced the overall cost to around 150 cycles.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] To gain performance and determinism, some systems place functions that would likely be viewed as application logic, rather than as device drivers, in kernel mode; security applications (access control, firewalls, etc.) and operating system monitors are cited as examples.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Functions are also sometimes moved across rings in the other direction.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] The Linux kernel, for instance, injects into processes a vDSO section which contains functions that would normally require a system call, i.e. a ring transition.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Instead of doing a syscall these functions use static data provided by the kernel.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] This avoids the need for a ring transition and so is more lightweight than a syscall.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] The function gettimeofday can be provided this way.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Recent CPUs from Intel and AMD offer x86 virtualization instructions for a hypervisor to control Ring 0 hardware access.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Although they are mutually incompatible, both Intel VT-x (codenamed "Vanderpool") and AMD-V (codenamed "Pacifica") allow a guest operating system to run Ring 0 operations natively without affecting other guests or the host OS.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Before hardware-assisted virtualization, guest operating systems ran under ring 1.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Any attempt that requires a higher privilege level to perform (ring 0) will produce an interrupt and then be handled using software; this is called "Trap and Emulate".
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] To assist virtualization and reduce overhead caused by the reason above, VT-x and AMD-V allow the guest to run under Ring 0.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] VT-x introduces VMX Root/Non-root Operation: The hypervisor runs in VMX Root Operation mode, possessing the highest privilege.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Guest OS runs in VMX Non-Root Operation mode, which allows them to operate at ring 0 without having actual hardware privileges.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] VMX non-root operation and VMX transitions are controlled by a data structure called a virtual-machine control.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] These hardware extensions allow classical "Trap and Emulate" virtualization to perform on x86 architecture but now with hardware support.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] A **privilege level** in the x86 instruction set controls the access of the program currently running on the processor to resources such as memory regions, I/O ports, and special instructions.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] There are 4 privilege levels ranging from 0 which is the most privileged, to 3 which is least privileged.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Most modern operating systems use level 0 for the kernel/executive, and use level 3 for application programs.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Any resource available to level n is also available to levels 0 to n, so the privilege levels are rings.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] When a lesser privileged process tries to access a higher privileged process, a general protection fault exception is reported to the OS.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] It is not necessary to use all four privilege levels.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Current operating systems with wide market share including Microsoft Windows, macOS, Linux, iOS and Android mostly use a paging mechanism with only one bit to specify the privilege level as either Supervisor or User (U/S Bit).
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Code running in real mode is executed at level 0 (highest privilege level) whereas code running in virtual-8086 mode is executed at level 3.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Potential future uses for the multiple privilege levels supported by the x86 ISA family include containerization and virtual machines.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] A host operating system kernel could use instructions with full privilege access (kernel mode), whereas applications running on the guest OS in a virtual machine or container could use the lowest level of privileges in user mode.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] The virtual machine and guest OS kernel could themselves use an intermediate level of instruction privilege to invoke and virtualize kernel-mode operations such as system calls from the point of view of the guest operating system.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] The **IOPL** (**I/O Privilege level**) flag is a flag found on all IA-32 compatible x86 CPUs.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] It occupies bits 12 and 13 in the FLAGS register.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] In protected mode and long mode, it shows the I/O privilege level of the current program or task.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] The Current Privilege Level (CPL) (CPL0, CPL1, CPL2, CPL3) of the task or program must be less than or equal to the IOPL in order for the task or program to access I/O ports.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] The IOPL can be changed using `POPF(D)` and `IRET(D)` only when the current privilege level is Ring 0.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Besides IOPL, the I/O Port Permissions in the TSS also take part in determining the ability of a task to access an I/O port.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] In x86 systems, the x86 hardware virtualization (VT-x and SVM) is referred as "ring −1", the System Management Mode is referred as "ring −2", the Intel Management Engine and AMD Platform Security Processor are sometimes referred as "ring −3".
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Many CPU hardware architectures provide far more flexibility than is exploited by the operating systems that they normally run.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Proper use of complex CPU modes requires very close cooperation between the operating system and the CPU, and thus tends to tie the OS to the CPU architecture.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] For example, the reason Windows uses only two levels (ring 0 and ring 3) is that some hardware architectures that were supported in the past (such as PowerPC or MIPS) implemented only two privilege levels.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Multics was an operating system designed specifically for a special CPU architecture (which in turn was designed specifically for Multics), and it took full advantage of the CPU modes available to it.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] However, it was an exception to the rule.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Today, this high degree of interoperation between the OS and the hardware is not often cost-effective, despite the potential advantages for security and stability.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Ultimately, the purpose of distinct operating modes for the CPU is to provide hardware protection against accidental or deliberate corruption of the system environment (and corresponding breaches of system security) by software.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Only "trusted" portions of system software are allowed to execute in the unrestricted environment of kernel mode, and then, in paradigmatic designs, only when absolutely necessary.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] All other software executes in one or more user modes.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] If a processor generates a fault or exception condition in a user mode, in most cases system stability is unaffected; if a processor generates a fault or exception condition in kernel mode, most operating systems will halt the system with an unrecoverable error.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] When a hierarchy of modes exists (ring-based security), faults and exceptions at one privilege level may destabilize only the higher-numbered privilege levels.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Thus, a fault in Ring 0 (the kernel mode with the highest privilege) will crash the entire system, but a fault in Ring 2 will only affect Rings 3 and beyond and Ring 2 itself, at most.
[src:arm-trustzone/protection-ring] Microkernel operating systems attempt to minimize the amount of code running in privileged mode, for purposes of security and elegance.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] A **system on a chip**, or **system on chip** (**SoC**), is an integrated circuit that combines most or all key components of a computer or electronic system onto a single microchip.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Typically, an SoC includes a central processing unit (CPU) with memory, input/output, and data storage control functions, along with optional features like a graphics processing unit (GPU), Wi-Fi connectivity, and radio frequency processing.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] This high level of integration minimizes the need for separate, discrete components, thereby enhancing power efficiency and simplifying device design.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] High-performance SoCs are often paired with dedicated memory, such as LPDDR, and flash storage chips, such as eUFS or eMMC, which may be stacked directly on top of the SoC in a package-on-package (PoP) configuration or placed nearby on the motherboard.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Some SoCs also operate alongside specialized chips, such as cellular modems.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Fundamentally, SoCs integrate one or more processor cores with critical peripherals.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] This comprehensive integration is conceptually similar to how a microcontroller is designed, but providing far greater computational power.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] This unified design delivers lower power consumption and a reduced semiconductor die area compared to traditional multi-chip architectures, though at the cost of reduced modularity and component replaceability.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoCs are ubiquitous in mobile computing, where compact, energy-efficient designs are critical.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] They power smartphones, tablets, and smartwatches, and are increasingly important in edge computing, where real-time data processing occurs close to the data source.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoCs can be applied to any computing task.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] However, they are typically used in mobile computing such as tablets, smartphones, smartwatches, and netbooks as well as embedded systems and in applications where previously microcontrollers would be used.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Where previously only microcontrollers could be used, SoCs are rising to prominence in the embedded systems market.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Tighter system integration offers better reliability and mean time between failures, and SoCs offer more advanced functionality and computing power than microcontrollers.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Applications include AI acceleration, embedded machine vision, data collection, telemetry, vector processing and ambient intelligence.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Often embedded SoCs target the internet of things, multimedia, networking, telecommunications and edge computing markets.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Some examples of SoCs for embedded applications include the STMicroelectronics STM32, the Raspberry Pi Ltd RP2040, and the AMD Zynq 7000.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Mobile computing based SoCs always bundle processors, memories, on-chip caches, wireless networking capabilities and often digital camera hardware and firmware.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] With increasing memory sizes, high end SoCs will often have no memory and flash storage and instead, the memory and flash memory will be placed right next to, or above (package on package), the SoC.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] In 1992, Acorn Computers produced the A3010, A3020 and A4000 range of personal computers with the ARM250 SoC.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] It combined the original Acorn ARM2 processor with a memory controller (MEMC), video controller (VIDC), and I/O controller (IOC).
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] In previous Acorn ARM-powered computers, these were four discrete chips.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] The ARM7500 chip was their second-generation SoC, based on the ARM700, VIDC20 and IOMD controllers, and was widely licensed in embedded devices such as set-top-boxes, as well as later Acorn personal computers.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] On modern laptops and mini PCs, the low-power variants of AMD Ryzen and Intel Core processors use SoC design integrating CPU, IGPU, chipset and other processors in a single package.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] However, such x86 processors still require external memory and storage chips.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] An SoC consists of hardware functional units, including microprocessors that run software code, as well as a communications subsystem to connect, control, direct and interface between these functional modules.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] An SoC must have at least one processor core, but typically an SoC has more than one core.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Processor cores can be a microcontroller, microprocessor (μP), digital signal processor (DSP) or application-specific instruction set processor (ASIP) core.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] ASIPs have instruction sets that are customized for an application domain and designed to be more efficient than general-purpose instructions for a specific type of workload.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Multiprocessor SoCs have more than one processor core by definition.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] The Arm architecture is a common choice for SoC processor cores because some Arm-architecture cores are soft processors specified as IP cores.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoCs must have semiconductor memory blocks to perform their computation, as do microcontrollers and other embedded systems.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Depending on the application, SoC memory may form a memory hierarchy and cache hierarchy.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] In the mobile computing market, this is common, but in many low-power embedded microcontrollers, this is not necessary.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Memory technologies for SoCs include read-only memory (ROM), random-access memory (RAM), Electrically Erasable Programmable ROM (EEPROM) and flash memory.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] As in other computer systems, RAM can be subdivided into relatively faster but more expensive static RAM (SRAM) and the slower but cheaper dynamic RAM (DRAM).
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] When an SoC has a cache hierarchy, SRAM will usually be used to implement processor registers and cores' built-in caches whereas DRAM will be used for main memory.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] "Main memory" may be specific to a single processor (which can be multi-core) when the SoC has multiple processors, in this case it is distributed memory and must be sent via § Intermodule communication on-chip to be accessed by a different processor.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] For further discussion of multi-processing memory issues, see cache coherence and memory latency.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoCs include external interfaces, typically for communication protocols.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] These are often based upon industry standards such as USB, Ethernet, USART, SPI, HDMI, I²C, CSI, etc.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] These interfaces will differ according to the intended application.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Wireless networking protocols such as Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, 6LoWPAN and near-field communication may also be supported.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] When needed, SoCs include analog interfaces including analog-to-digital and digital-to-analog converters, often for signal processing.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] These may be able to interface with different types of sensors or actuators, including smart transducers.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] They may interface with application-specific modules or shields.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Or they may be internal to the SoC, such as if an analog sensor is built in to the SoC and its readings must be converted to digital signals for mathematical processing.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Digital signal processor (DSP) cores are often included on SoCs.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] They perform signal processing operations in SoCs for sensors, actuators, data collection, data analysis and multimedia processing.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] DSP cores typically feature very long instruction word (VLIW) and single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) instruction set architectures, and are therefore highly amenable to exploiting instruction-level parallelism through parallel processing and superscalar execution.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SP cores most often feature application-specific instructions, and as such are typically application-specific instruction set processors (ASIP).
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Such application-specific instructions correspond to dedicated hardware functional units that compute those instructions.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Typical DSP instructions include multiply-accumulate, Fast Fourier transform, fused multiply-add, and convolutions.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] As with other computer systems, SoCs require timing sources to generate clock signals, control execution of SoC functions and provide time context to signal processing applications of the SoC, if needed.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Popular time sources are crystal oscillators and phase-locked loops.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoC peripherals including counter-timers, real-time timers and power-on reset generators.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoCs also include voltage regulators and power management circuits.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] These units must often send data and instructions back and forth.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Because of this, all but the most trivial SoCs require communications subsystems.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Originally, as with other microcomputer technologies, data bus architectures were used, but recently designs based on sparse intercommunication networks known as networks-on-chip (NoC) have risen to prominence and are forecast to overtake bus architectures for SoC design in the near future.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Historically, a shared global computer bus typically connected the different components, also called "blocks" of the SoC.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] A very common bus for SoC communications is Arm's royalty-free Advanced Microcontroller Bus Architecture (AMBA) standard.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Direct memory access controllers route data directly between external interfaces and SoC memory, bypassing the CPU or control unit, thereby increasing the data throughput of the SoC.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] This is similar to some device drivers of peripherals on component-based multi-chip module PC architectures.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Wire delay is not scalable due to continued miniaturization, system performance does not scale with the number of cores attached, the SoC's operating frequency must decrease with each additional core attached for power to be sustainable, and long wires consume large amounts of electrical power.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] These challenges are prohibitive to supporting manycore systems on chip.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] In the late 2010s, a trend of SoCs implementing communications subsystems in terms of a network-like topology instead of bus-based protocols has emerged.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] A trend towards more processor cores on SoCs has caused on-chip communication efficiency to become one of the key factors in determining the overall system performance and cost.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] This has led to the emergence of interconnection networks with router-based packet switching known as "networks on chip" (NoCs) to overcome the bottlenecks of bus-based networks.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Networks-on-chip have advantages including destination- and application-specific routing, greater power efficiency and reduced possibility of bus contention.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Network-on-chip architectures take inspiration from communication protocols like TCP and the Internet protocol suite for on-chip communication, although they typically have fewer network layers.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Optimal network-on-chip network architectures are an ongoing area of much research interest.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] NoC architectures range from traditional distributed computing network topologies such as torus, hypercube, meshes and tree networks to genetic algorithm scheduling to randomized algorithms such as random walks with branching and randomized time to live (TTL).
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Many SoC researchers consider NoC architectures to be the future of SoC design because they have been shown to efficiently meet power and throughput needs of SoC designs.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Current NoC architectures are two-dimensional.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] 2D IC design has limited floorplanning choices as the number of cores in SoCs increase, so as three-dimensional integrated circuits (3DICs) emerge, SoC designers are looking towards building three-dimensional on-chip networks known as 3DNoCs.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] A system on a chip consists of both the hardware, described in § Structure, and the software controlling the microcontroller, microprocessor or digital signal processor cores, peripherals and interfaces.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] The design flow for an SoC aims to develop this hardware and software at the same time, also known as architectural co-design.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] The design flow must also take into account optimizations (§ Optimization goals) and constraints.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Most SoCs are developed from pre-qualified hardware component IP core specifications for the hardware elements and execution units, collectively "blocks", described above, together with software device drivers that may control their operation.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Of particular importance are the protocol stacks that drive industry-standard interfaces like USB.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] The hardware blocks are put together using computer-aided design tools, specifically electronic design automation tools; the software modules are integrated using a software integrated development environment.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoCs components are also often designed in high-level programming languages such as C++, MATLAB or SystemC and converted to RTL designs through high-level synthesis (HLS) tools such as C to HDL or flow to HDL.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] HLS products called "algorithmic synthesis" allow designers to use C++ to model and synthesize system, circuit, software and verification levels all in one high level language commonly known to computer engineers in a manner independent of time scales, which are typically specified in HDL.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Other components can remain software and be compiled and embedded onto soft-core processors included in the SoC as modules in HDL as IP cores.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Once the architecture of the SoC has been defined, any new hardware elements are written in an abstract hardware description language termed register-transfer level (RTL) which defines the circuit behavior, or synthesized into RTL from a high level language through high-level synthesis.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] These elements are connected together in a hardware description language to create the full SoC design.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] The logic specified to connect these components and convert between possibly different interfaces provided by different vendors is called glue logic.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Chips are verified for validation correctness before being sent to a semiconductor foundry.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] This process is called functional verification and it accounts for a significant portion of the time and energy expended in the chip design life cycle, often quoted as 70%.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] With the growing complexity of chips, hardware verification languages like SystemVerilog, SystemC, e, and OpenVera are being used.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Bugs found in the verification stage are reported to the designer.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Traditionally, engineers have employed simulation acceleration, emulation or prototyping on reprogrammable hardware to verify and debug hardware and software for SoC designs prior to the finalization of the design, known as tape-out.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs) are favored for prototyping SoCs because FPGA prototypes are reprogrammable, allow debugging and are more flexible than application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs).
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] With high capacity and fast compilation time, simulation acceleration and emulation are powerful technologies that provide wide visibility into systems.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Both technologies, however, operate slowly, on the order of MHz, which may be significantly slower – up to 100 times slower – than the SoC's operating frequency.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Acceleration and emulation boxes are also very large and expensive at over US$1 million.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] FPGA prototypes, in contrast, use FPGAs directly to enable engineers to validate and test at, or close to, a system's full operating frequency with real-world stimuli.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Tools such as Certus are used to insert probes in the FPGA RTL that make signals available for observation.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] This is used to debug hardware, firmware and software interactions across multiple FPGAs with capabilities similar to a logic analyzer.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] In parallel, the hardware elements are grouped and passed through a process of logic synthesis, during which performance constraints, such as operational frequency and expected signal delays, are applied.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] This generates an output known as a netlist describing the design as a physical circuit and its interconnections.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] These netlists are combined with the glue logic connecting the components to produce the schematic description of the SoC as a circuit which can be printed onto a chip.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] This process is known as place and route and precedes tape-out in the event that the SoCs are produced as application-specific integrated circuits (ASIC).
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoCs must optimize power use, area on die, communication, positioning for locality between modular units and other factors.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Optimization is necessarily a design goal of SoCs.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] If optimization was not necessary, the engineers would use a multi-chip module architecture without accounting for the area use, power consumption or performance of the system to the same extent.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Common optimization targets for SoC designs follow, with explanations of each.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] In general, optimizing any of these quantities may be a hard combinatorial optimization problem, and can indeed be NP-hard fairly easily.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Therefore, sophisticated optimization algorithms are often required and it may be practical to use approximation algorithms or heuristics in some cases.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Additionally, most SoC designs contain multiple variables to optimize simultaneously, so Pareto efficient solutions are sought after in SoC design.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Oftentimes the goals of optimizing some of these quantities are directly at odds, further adding complexity to design optimization of SoCs and introducing trade-offs in system design.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] For broader coverage of trade-offs and requirements analysis, see requirements engineering.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoCs are optimized to minimize the electrical power used to perform the SoC's functions.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoC systems often require long battery life (such as smartphones), can potentially spend months or years without a power source while needing to maintain autonomous function, and often are limited in power use by a high number of embedded SoCs being networked together in an area.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Additionally, energy costs can be high and conserving energy will reduce the total cost of ownership of the SoC.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Finally, waste heat from high energy consumption can damage other circuit components if too much heat is dissipated, giving another pragmatic reason to conserve energy.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] The amount of energy used in a circuit is the integral of power consumed with respect to time, and the average rate of power consumption is the product of current by voltage.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] $P=IV={\frac {V^{2}}{R}}={I^{2}}{R}$ SoCs are frequently embedded in portable devices such as smartphones, GPS navigation devices, digital watches (including smartwatches) and netbooks.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Customers want long battery lives for mobile computing devices, another reason that power consumption must be minimized in SoCs.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Multimedia applications are often executed on these devices, including video games, video streaming, image processing; all of which have grown in computational complexity in recent years with user demands and expectations for higher-quality multimedia.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Computation is more demanding as expectations move towards 3D video at high resolution with multiple standards, so SoCs performing multimedia tasks must be computationally capable platform while being low power to run off a standard mobile battery.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoCs are optimized to maximize power efficiency in performance per watt: maximize the performance of the SoC given a budget of power usage.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Many applications such as edge computing, distributed processing and ambient intelligence require a certain level of computational performance, but power is limited in most SoC environments.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoC designs are optimized to minimize waste heat output on the chip.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] As with other integrated circuits, heat generated due to high power density are the bottleneck to further miniaturization of components.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] The power densities of high speed integrated circuits, particularly microprocessors and including SoCs, have become highly uneven.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Too much waste heat can damage circuits and erode reliability of the circuit over time.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] High temperatures and thermal stress negatively impact reliability, stress migration, decreased mean time between failures, electromigration, wire bonding, metastability and other performance degradation of the SoC over time.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] In particular, most SoCs are in a small physical area or volume and therefore the effects of waste heat are compounded because there is little room for it to diffuse out of the system.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Because of high transistor counts on modern devices, oftentimes a layout of sufficient throughput and high transistor density is physically realizable from fabrication processes but would result in unacceptably high amounts of heat in the circuit's volume.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] These thermal effects force SoC and other chip designers to apply conservative design margins, creating less performant devices to mitigate the risk of catastrophic failure.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Due to increased transistor densities as length scales get smaller, each process generation produces more heat output than the last.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Compounding this problem, SoC architectures are usually heterogeneous, creating spatially inhomogeneous heat fluxes, which cannot be effectively mitigated by uniform passive cooling.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoCs are optimized to maximize computational and communications throughput.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoCs are optimized to minimize latency for some or all of their functions.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] This can be accomplished by laying out elements with proper proximity and locality to each-other to minimize the interconnection delays and maximize the speed at which data is communicated between modules, functional units and memories.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] In general, optimizing to minimize latency is an NP-complete problem equivalent to the Boolean satisfiability problem.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] For tasks running on processor cores, latency and throughput can be improved with task scheduling.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Some tasks run in application-specific hardware units, however, and even task scheduling may not be sufficient to optimize all software-based tasks to meet timing and throughput constraints.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Systems on chip are modeled with standard hardware verification and validation techniques, but additional techniques are used to model and optimize SoC design alternatives to make the system optimal with respect to multiple-criteria decision analysis on the above optimization targets.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Task scheduling is an important activity in any computer system with multiple processes or threads sharing a single processor core.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] It is important to reduce § Latency and increase § Throughput for embedded software running on an SoC's § Processor cores.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Not every important computing activity in a SoC is performed in software running on on-chip processors, but scheduling can drastically improve performance of software-based tasks and other tasks involving shared resources.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Software running on SoCs often schedules tasks according to network scheduling and randomized scheduling algorithms.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Hardware and software tasks are often pipelined in processor design.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Pipelining is an important principle for speedup in computer architecture.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] They are frequently used in CPUs (for example, the classic RISC pipeline) and GPUs (graphics pipeline), but are also applied to application-specific tasks such as digital signal processing and multimedia manipulations in the context of SoCs.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoCs are often analyzed though probabilistic models, queueing networks, and Markov chains.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] For instance, Little's law allows SoC states and NoC buffers to be modeled as arrival processes and analyzed through Poisson random variables and Poisson processes.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoCs are often modeled with Markov chains, both discrete time and continuous time variants.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Markov chain modeling allows asymptotic analysis of the SoC's steady state distribution of power, heat, latency and other factors to allow design decisions to be optimized for the common case.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoC chips are typically fabricated using metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] The netlists described above are used as the basis for the physical design (place and route) flow to convert the designers' intent into the design of the SoC.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] When all known bugs have been rectified and these have been re-verified and all physical design checks are done, the physical design files describing each layer of the chip are sent to the foundry's mask shop where a full set of glass lithographic masks will be etched.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] These are sent to a wafer fabrication plant to create the SoC dice before packaging and testing.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] ASICs consume less power and are faster than FPGAs but cannot be reprogrammed and are expensive to manufacture.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] FPGA designs are more suitable for lower volume designs, but after enough units of production ASICs reduce the total cost of ownership.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoC designs consume less power and have a lower cost and higher reliability than the multi-chip systems that they replace.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] With fewer packages in the system, assembly costs are reduced as well.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] However, like most very-large-scale integration (VLSI) designs, the total cost is higher for one large chip than for the same functionality distributed over several smaller chips, because of lower yields and higher non-recurring engineering costs.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] When it is not feasible to construct an SoC for a particular application, an alternative is a system in package (SiP) comprising a number of chips in a single package.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] When produced in large volumes, SoC is more cost-effective than SiP because its packaging is simpler.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Another reason SiP may be preferred is waste heat may be too high in a SoC for a given purpose because functional components are too close together, and in an SiP heat will dissipate better from different functional modules since they are physically further apart.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] SoC research and development often compares many options.
[src:arm-trustzone/system-on-a-chip] Benchmarks, such as COSMIC, are developed to help such evaluations.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] A **trusted execution environment** (**TEE**) is a secure area of a main processor.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] It helps the code and data loaded inside it be protected with respect to confidentiality and integrity.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] Data confidentiality prevents unauthorized entities from outside the TEE from reading data, while code integrity prevents code in the TEE from being replaced or modified by unauthorized entities, which may also be the computer owner itself as in certain DRM schemes described in Intel SGX.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] This is done by implementing unique, immutable, and confidential architectural security, which offers hardware-based memory encryption that isolates specific application code and data in memory.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] This allows user-level code to allocate private regions of memory, called enclaves, which are designed to be protected from processes running at higher privilege levels.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] A TEE as an isolated execution environment provides security features such as isolated execution, integrity of applications executing with the TEE, and confidentiality of their assets.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] In general terms, the TEE offers an execution space that provides a higher level of security for trusted applications running on the device than a rich operating system (OS) and more functionality than a 'secure element' (SE).
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] The first security level, Profile 1, was targeted against only software attacks, while Profile 2, was targeted against both software and hardware attacks.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] Commercial TEE solutions based on ARM TrustZone technology, conforming to the TR1 standard, were later launched, such as Trusted Foundations developed by Trusted Logic.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] Work on the OMTP standards ended in mid-2010 when the group transitioned into the Wholesale Applications Community (WAC).
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] The OMTP standards, including those defining a TEE, are hosted by GSMA.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE typically consists of a hardware isolation mechanism plus a secure operating system running on top of that isolation mechanism, although the term has been used more generally to mean a protected solution.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] Whilst a GlobalPlatform TEE requires hardware isolation, others, such as EMVCo, use the term TEE to refer to both hardware and software-based solutions.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] FIDO uses the concept of TEE in the restricted operating environment for TEEs based on hardware isolation.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] Only trusted applications running in a TEE have access to the full power of a device's main processor, peripherals, and memory, while hardware isolation protects these from user-installed apps running in a main operating system.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] Software and cryptography inside the TEE protects the trusted applications contained within from each other.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] Service providers, mobile network operators (MNO), operating system developers, application developers, device manufacturers, platform providers, and silicon vendors are the main stakeholders contributing to the standardization efforts around the TEE.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] To prevent the simulation of hardware with user-controlled software, a so-called "hardware root of trust" is used.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] This is a set of private keys that are embedded directly into the chip during manufacturing; one-time programmable memory such as eFuses is usually used on mobile devices.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] The hardware is designed in a way that prevents all software not signed by the trusted party's key from accessing the privileged features.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] The public key of the vendor is provided at runtime and hashed; this hash is then compared to the one embedded in the chip.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] If the hash matches, the public key is used to verify a digital signature of trusted vendor-controlled firmware (such as a chain of bootloaders on Android devices or 'architectural enclaves' in SGX).
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] The trusted firmware is then used to implement remote attestation.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] When an application is attested, its untrusted components loads its trusted component into memory; the trusted application is protected from modification by untrusted components with hardware.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] A nonce is requested by the untrusted party from the verifier's server and is used as part of a cryptographic authentication protocol, proving integrity of the trusted application.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] The proof is passed to the verifier, which verifies it.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] A valid proof cannot be computed in simulated hardware (i.e.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] QEMU) because in order to construct it, access to the keys baked into hardware is required; only trusted firmware has access to these keys and/or the keys derived from them or obtained using them.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] Because only the platform owner is meant to have access to the data recorded in the foundry, the verifying party must interact with the service set up by the vendor.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] If the scheme is implemented improperly, the chip vendor can track which applications are used on which chip and selectively deny service by returning a message indicating that authentication has not passed.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] To simulate hardware in a way that enables it to pass remote authentication, an attacker would have to extract keys from the hardware, which is costly because of the equipment and technical skill required to execute it.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] For example, using focused ion beams, scanning electron microscopes, microprobing, and chip decapsulation is difficult, or even impossible, if the hardware is designed in such a way that reverse-engineering destroys the keys.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] In most cases, the keys are unique for each piece of hardware, so that a key extracted from one chip cannot be used by others (for example physically unclonable functions).
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] Note: Much TEE literature covers this topic under the definition "premium content protection," which is the preferred nomenclature of many copyright holders.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] Premium content protection is a specific use case of digital rights management (DRM) and is controversial among some communities, such as the Free Software Foundation.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] It is widely used by copyright holders to restrict the ways in which end users can consume content such as 4K high-definition films.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE is a suitable environment for protecting digitally encoded information (for example, HD films or audio) on connected devices such as smartphones, tablets, and HD televisions.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] This suitability comes from the ability of the TEE to deprive the owner of the device of access stored secrets, and the fact that there is often a protected hardware path between the TEE and the display and/or subsystems on devices.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE is used to protect the content once it is on the device.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] While the content is protected during transmission or streaming by the use of encryption, the TEE protects the content once it has been decrypted on the device by ensuring that decrypted content is not exposed to the environment not approved by the app developer or platform vendor.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] Mobile commerce applications such as: mobile wallets, peer-to-peer payments, contactless payments or using a mobile device as a point of sale (POS) terminal often have well-defined security requirements.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] In some scenarios, interaction with the end user is required, and this may require the user to expose sensitive information such as a PIN, password, or biometric identifier to the mobile OS as a means of authenticating the user.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE optionally offers a trusted user interface which can be used to construct user authentication on a mobile device.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] With the rise of cryptocurrency, TEEs are increasingly used to implement crypto-wallets, as they offer the ability to store tokens more securely than regular operating systems, and can provide the necessary computation and authentication applications.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE is well-suited for supporting biometric identification methods (facial recognition, fingerprint sensor, and voice authorization), which may be easier to use and harder to steal than PINs and passwords.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] A TEE is a good area within a mobile device to house the matching engine and the associated processing required to authenticate the user.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] The environment is designed to protect the data and establish a buffer against the non-secure apps located in mobile OSes.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] This additional security may help to satisfy the security needs of service providers in addition to keeping the costs low for handset developers.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE can be used by governments, enterprises, and cloud service providers to enable the secure handling of confidential information on mobile devices and on server infrastructure.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE offers a level of protection against software attacks generated in the mobile OS and assists in the control of access rights.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] It achieves this by housing sensitive, ‘trusted’ applications that need to be isolated and protected from the mobile OS and any malicious malware that may be present.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] Through utilizing the functionality and security levels offered by the TEE, governments, and enterprises can be assured that employees using their own devices are doing so in a secure and trusted manner.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] Likewise, server-based TEEs help defend against internal and external attacks against backend infrastructure.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] With the rise of software assets and reuses, modular programming is the most productive process to design software architecture, by decoupling the functionalities into small independent modules.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] As each module contains everything necessary to execute its desired functionality, the TEE allows the organization of the complete system featuring a high level of reliability and security, while preventing each module from vulnerabilities of the others.
[src:arm-trustzone/trusted-execution-environment] In order for the modules to communicate and share data, TEE provides means to securely have payloads sent/received between the modules, using mechanisms such as object serialization, in conjunction with proxies.
